# React Component Rules (module-specific)

These rules apply **only to `.tsx` files** containing React components.

## Component Structure

- One component per file; file name must match the exported component name in PascalCase.
- Export the component as a named export; avoid default exports for components (improves refactor safety).
- Place prop types/interfaces directly above the component definition in the same file.
- Keep components focused — if a component exceeds ~150 lines, consider splitting into smaller sub-components.

## Props

- Define props with an `interface` named `<ComponentName>Props`.
- Destructure props at the top of the function body.
- Use explicit `React.FC` or typed arrow functions; prefer the latter to allow generic components.
- Mark optional props with `?`; provide sensible defaults via destructuring defaults, not inside JSX.

## Hooks

- Call hooks at the top level — never inside conditionals, loops, or nested functions.
- Custom hooks must be prefixed with `use` and live in a `hooks/` directory.
- Avoid creating new object/array literals directly inside `useMemo`/`useCallback` dependency arrays.

## Performance

- Wrap expensive child trees with `React.memo` only when profiling confirms unnecessary re-renders.
- Prefer `useCallback` for stable event handlers passed to memoized children.
- Avoid inline anonymous functions in JSX for performance-critical components (e.g., canvas overlays).

## Accessibility

- Every interactive element must have an accessible label (`aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, or visible text).
- Use semantic HTML elements (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`) before resorting to `<div>` with role.

## How to Verify

1. Run `yarn test:code` — ESLint React rules must pass with zero warnings.
2. Check that every new `.tsx` file contains at most one exported component.
3. Run `yarn test:typecheck` — prop interfaces must satisfy TypeScript strict mode.
4. Search for missing `aria-label` on `<button>` elements:
   ```bash
   grep -r "<button" packages/excalidraw/src --include="*.tsx" | grep -v "aria-"
   ```
   Investigate any matches to confirm they have accessible text via children.
